- `int` is a numeric type.
- `int.class` is a class literal.

&gt; A class literal is an expression consisting of the name of a class, interface, array, or **primitive type**, or the pseudo-type `void`, followed by a `.` and the token class.
&gt;
&gt; `ClassLiteral`:
&gt;
&gt; - `TypeName {[ ]} . class`
&gt; - **`NumericType {[ ]} . class`** 
&gt; - `boolean {[ ]} . class `
&gt; - `void . class`
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;sup&gt;[JLS 10 - 15.8.2. Class Literals][1]&lt;/sup&gt;

Moreover, 

    Class&lt;Integer&gt; intClass = int.class;

according to 

&gt; The type of `p.class`, where p is the name of a primitive type ([&#167;4.2][2]), is `Class&lt;B&gt;`, where `B` is the type of an expression of type `p` after boxing conversion ([&#167;5.1.7][3]).
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;sup&gt;[JLS 10 - 15.8.2. Class Literals][1]&lt;/sup&gt;


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se10/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.8.2
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se10/html/jls-4.html#jls-4.2
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se10/html/jls-5.html#jls-5.1.7

